# Project Overview
You are a Senior Flutter Developer building an MVP for an Elevator Maintenance & Fault Tracking System. 
The app is designed for Elevator Technicians and Building Residents.

# Tech Stack
- Frontend: Flutter (Dart)
- Backend/Database: Supabase (PostgreSQL, Auth, Storage)
- State Management: flutter_riverpod (Riverpod)
- Routing: go_router
- Styling: Material Design 3 (Keep UI components basic and modular, as the actual UI code will be imported from an external design tool).

# Architecture (Feature-First)
Enforce a feature-first folder structure. Never mix feature logic.
lib/
  ├── core/             # Shared utilities, constants, theme, network, router
  ├── features/
  │   ├── auth/         # Login, Supabase Auth integration
  │   ├── elevator/     # QR Scanning, Elevator Details
  │   ├── maintenance/  # Maintenance logs, forms
  │   └── fault/        # Fault reporting, list of faults
  └── main.dart

# Database Schema Context (Supabase)
- `elevators`: id (uuid), building_name, address, status
- `fault_reports`: id (uuid), elevator_id, description, photo_url, is_resolved, reported_at
- `maintenance_logs`: id (uuid), elevator_id, technician_id, notes, is_approved, maintenance_date

# Coding Rules
1. ALWAYS use `flutter_riverpod` for state management. Do not use setState unless absolutely necessary for simple local UI state.
2. Separate business logic from UI. Repositories should handle Supabase calls; Riverpod Providers should manage state.
3. Handle Supabase exceptions gracefully and return User-Friendly error messages.
4. Keep UI placeholder-friendly. Build functional widgets (Forms, Lists, Buttons) but do not over-engineer the styling. The user will replace the UI layer later.
5. Do NOT use mock data. Write the code to connect directly to Supabase using the `supabase_flutter` package.
6. Write null-safe, clean, and well-documented Dart code.